04794nam a22005775i 9781503634039DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036340397 a10.1515/97815036340392doi  a(DE-B1597)632983  a(OCoLC)1309291466  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0470002bisacsh04a305.230985/255223//eng/20220404eng1 aLuttrell-Rowland, Mikaela, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitical Children :bViolence, Labor, and Rights in Peru /cMikaela Luttrell-Rowland. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (266 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Learning How to Describe the State: The Everyday Lives of Young People in Lima -- tPart I -- t1 Listening Between Generations: Past and Present Violence in Lomas -- t2 Deferred Promises: How Young People Describe Injustice in Lomas -- t3 Stories of a Visual Landscape: Murals, Slogans, and Margins in Lomas -- tPart II -- t4 Young People Together: Children, Protagonism, and Organized Labor -- t5 Child Workers and Child Citizens: Rights, Recognition, and the Language of Equality -- t6 Looking for the State: The Politics of Children’s Participation in Peru -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPolitical Children argues for new methods of listening to marginalized young people so as to better understand everyday practices of state power and violence. Grounded in extensive interviews, longitudinal ethnography, historical analysis, and archival work, Mikaela Luttrell-Rowland shows how two separate groups of working young people in Lima, Peru, have become political protagonists, resisting and critiquing inequality and injustice. She details the ways they interpret and address a range of issues affecting their lives—from environmental degradation to second-rate public facilities, gender-based violence to dangerous working conditions—and reveals how by organizing and fighting systemic marginalization they make sense of state violence, and of their own labor. By attending to the affect, longing, and desires that animate these young people's politics, Luttrell-Rowland conveys the meaning of their lives and work in an economy that invokes their subjectivity and rights while rendering them non-participatory subjects. Though the lives of young people are often imagined as far from politics, these "political children" expose the contradictions of public policy narratives in which the Peruvian state is cast as a neutral site for engagement and action. Through their criticism and activism, the young people in this book demonstrate that such narratives divorce state power from the very places in which it is experienced as structural violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englishz978311131926108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023z9783111318806oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z97831107913270 cprintz978150363336040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363403940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503634039423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503634039/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press C